Step-by-step implementation with data-proven milestones
Step 1: Define cohort and endpoints (Weeks 1-2).
Select one population (e.g., uncontrolled hypertension + diabetes overlap). Define primary endpoints (adherence, alert-to-action time, exacerbation proxy, RPM completeness). Baseline current performance from retrospective data.

Step 2: Build data backbone (Weeks 2-5).
Integrate wearables, meds, labs, and EHR feeds into PostgreSQL (+ Timescale). Standardize patient timeline schema. Validate data quality and missingness patterns.

Step 3: Deploy clinical guardrails first (Weeks 4-6).
Implement deterministic thresholds and escalation logic reviewed by clinicians. This creates a safe minimum product before adaptive AI.

Step 4: Add anomaly detection (Weeks 6-8).
Train patient-specific deviation models on historical data. Measure precision/recall against clinician-reviewed events; tune for low false-negative risk.

Step 5: Launch patient copilot via MCP (Weeks 7-9).
Use FastMCP tools for timeline retrieval, risk explanation, nudge generation, escalation creation, and audit logging. Keep all clinical actions tool-mediated and auditable.

Step 6: Introduce adaptive nudging (Weeks 9-12).
Start with contextual bandits (safer than full RL). Optimize nudge timing/channel/content using response feedback. Maintain hard clinical overrides.

Step 7: FHIR care-team integration (Weeks 10-12).
Create structured FHIR Task/CommunicationRequest outputs with severity/rationale fields and SLA routing.

Step 8: Evidence and reimbursement layer (parallel).
Capture interaction minutes, device active days, intervention logs, and care-team communication artifacts for RPM evidence completeness.

Step 9: Pilot evaluation (Month 4-6).
Compare intervention cohort vs baseline/historical controls on clinical and operational KPIs. Produce evidence package for expansion and patent support.

